description: From Middle French prothoplaste, and its source Late Latin protoplastus, from Hellenistic Ancient Greek πρωτόπλαστος (prōtóplastos, “first-formed”), from Ancient Greek πρωτο- (prōto-) + πλαστός (plastós, “formed, moulded”).

adjectives.description: protoplast (comparative more protoplast, superlative most protoplast)

entries.meaning: (rare) A prototype or archetype; a model. [from 17th c.]
The first person in a given family, lineage etc.; an ancestor. [from 17th c.]
examples: Habsburg tradition insists that the protoplast of the family was called Guntram.

entries.meaning: (biology) The contents of a plant cell. [from 19th c.]
